[[File:Murayama-jinja (Kameoka) torii.JPG|thumb|200px|right|{{center|Torii}}]]
'''Murayama Shrine''' (むらやまじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Mori, Shino-chō, {{ill|lt=Kameoka|Q633996|qid=Q633996|1=Kameoka, Kyoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|qid=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}. Its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The enshrined deities are as follows.
; Main deities (honden)
:* {{ill|qid=Q386563|lt=Ōyamatsumi|Q386563|qid=Q386563|lt=Ōyamazumi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōyamatsumi}} (おおやまづみのみこと)
:* {{ill|lt=Konohanasakuya-hime|UNKNOWN|lt=Konohanasakuya-hime-no-Mikoto}} (このはなさくやひめのみこと)
; Associated deities (Hachiman-gū)
:* {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|qid=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}}
:* {{ill|lt=Emperor Nintoku|Q313119|qid=Q313119|1=Emperor Nintoku}}

=== History ===
Founding is unknown for both honden and Hachiman-gū. Kiln remains such as Sue ware have been found on the plateau behind the precinct, and shards are also confirmed from the back mountain.

In the {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=register of deities|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} of the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' completed in {{ill|lt=Enchō (era)|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|lt=Enchō|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}), "Murayama Shrine" is listed in {{ill|lt=Kuwata District|Q11537600|qid=Q11537600|1=Kuwada district}} of Tanba Province, and ranked as {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}.

Shrine tradition says it once had vast shrine lands but burned in warfare; in {{ill|lt=Ōei|Q1193078|qid=Q1193078|1=Ōei}} 27 ({{ill|lt=1420|Q6209|qid=Q6209|1=1420}}), Watanabe Rokurō Yorikata, administrator of Kokuon-ji who governed this area, restored shrine buildings, and around that time invited Hachiman-gū to stand alongside<ref>'Place Names of Kyoto Prefecture,' Murayama Shrine section.</ref>.

In {{ill|lt=2017|Q25290|qid=Q25290|1=2017}} ({{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|qid=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 29), Hachiman-gū honden collapsed due to {{ill|lt=Typhoon 21 (2017)|Q42108577|qid=Q42108577|lt=Typhoon 21|1=Typhoon Lan (2017)}}<ref>[https://www.sankei.com/article/20180214-MTZP3UOMHFNCNGABYEAKXISHMA/ "Kyoto Prefecture subsidizes 12 undesignated cultural property repairs for typhoon damage, 4.83 million yen"] (Sankei Shimbun, Feb 14, 2018).</ref>.

